-Shtern brings this golden age to life, looking at dozens of shtetls and drawing on a wealth of never-before-used archival material. Illustrated throughout with rare archival photographs and artwork, this nuanced history casts the shtetl in an altogether new light, revealing how its golden age continues to shape the collective memory of the Jewish people today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aHistoryxJewish. 0aHistory. 0aJewsxSocial life and customs. 0aJewszEurope, EasternxSocial life and customs. 0aShtetlszEurope, EasternxHistory. 0aVillageszEurope, EasternxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAgunah.  aAntisemitism.  aArson.  aBanknote.  aBeit Hatfutsot.  aBelarus.  aBratslav.  aBrewery.  aBribery.  aBureaucrat.  aCatherine the Great.  aChabad.  aCommodity.  aConscription.  aContraband.  aCorporal punishment.  aCourtesy.  aCrime.  aDerazhnia.  aDwelling.  aEastern Galicia.  aFamine.  aFree trade.  aHasid (term).  aHebrew University of Jerusalem.  aHorse theft.  aHousehold.  aHumiliation.  aIdeology.  aIncome.  aIsaac Bashevis Singer.  aJews.  aJudaism.  aKabbalah.  aKerchief.  aKorets.  aKremenets.  aLand of Israel.  aLandlord.  aLithuania.  aLviv.  aMagnate.  aMarket town.  aMinyan.  aMogilev.  aMoses.  aNarrative.  aNewspaper.  aNickname.  aObscenity.  aOstrog (fortress).  aPale of Settlement.  aPartitions of Poland.  aPaul I of Russia.  aPeasant.  aPersecution.  aPodolia.  aPogrom.  aPoles.  aPretext.  aPrinting press.  aProverb.  aPurim.  aRadomyshl.  aRebbe.  aResidence.  aRetail.  aRoman Vishniac.  aRuble.  aRural area.  aRussian nationalism.  aRussians.  aRuzhin (Hasidic dynasty).  aS. Ansky.  aSamovar.  aSerfdom.  aShaul Stampfer.  aS